terraform
# AWS Infrastructure
resource "aws_ecs_cluster" "notification_platform" {
  name = "notification-platform"
  
  setting {
    name  = "containerInsights"
    value = "enabled"
  }
}

resource "aws_ecs_service" "notification_platform" {
  name            = "notification-platform"
  cluster         = aws_ecs_cluster.notification_platform.id
  task_definition = aws_ecs_task_definition.notification_platform.arn
  desired_count   = 5
  
  deployment_configuration {
    maximum_percent         = 200
    minimum_healthy_percent = 100
  }
  
  load_balancer {
    target_group_arn = aws_lb_target_group.notification_platform.arn
    container_name   = "notification-platform"
    container_port   = 8080
  }
}

resource "aws_sqs_queue" "notification_queues" {
  for_each = toset(["mobile", "desktop", "teams"])
  
  name                       = "${each.value}-notifications"
  message_retention_seconds  = 1209600  # 14 days
  visibility_timeout_seconds = 300      # 5 minutes
  
  redrive_policy = jsonencode({
    deadLetterTargetArn = aws_sqs_queue.notification_dlq[each.key].arn
    maxReceiveCount     = 3
  })
}

resource "aws_sqs_queue" "notification_dlq" {
  for_each = toset(["mobile", "desktop", "teams"])
  
  name                       = "${each.value}-notifications-dlq"
  message_retention_seconds  = 1209600
}
ğŸ“Š Technical Performance Summary
Scalability Metrics
yaml
Current Capacity:
  notifications_per_day: 50M
  concurrent_users: 100K
  peak_requests_per_second: 25K
  database_size: 5TB
  cache_hit_rate: 95%

Scaling Limits:
  horizontal_scaling: Auto-scale 3-50 instances
  database_scaling: Sharded MongoDB cluster
  cache_scaling: Redis cluster with failover
  queue_scaling: SQS with auto-scaling triggers

Resource Efficiency:
  average_cpu_per_notification: 0.5ms
  average_memory_per_notification: 2KB
  database_operations_per_notification: 3
  cache_lookups_per_notification: 5
Reliability Metrics
yaml
Availability:
  uptime_target: 99.9%
  actual_uptime: 99.95%
  mttr: 15 minutes
  mtbf: 720 hours

Fault Tolerance:
  database_replication: 3 replicas
  service_redundancy: Multi-AZ deployment
  queue_persistence: Durable message storage
  circuit_breaker_protection: Enabled on all external calls

Data Integrity:
  message_delivery_guarantee: At-least-once
  duplicate_detection: 30-second window
  data_consistency: Eventually consistent
  backup_strategy: Daily snapshots + transaction logs
This technical architecture provides a robust, scalable, and maintainable platform that can handle enterprise-scale notification workloads while maintaining high performance, security, and reliability standards.

summarize end to end use case flowfor easy explaination and decision points.

End-to-End Use Case Flow: Simplified Decision Framework
ğŸ¯ Use Case: John Books a Desk - Platform-Specific Notifications
Business Context
Actor: John Doe (Employee)
Action: Books Desk 42A for tomorrow via MyWorkspace app
Devices: Has iPhone + MacBook (both with MyWorkspace installed)
Expectation: Get appropriate notifications on both devices
ğŸ“‹ Step-by-Step Flow with Decision Points
Phase 1: Setup (One-Time Configuration)
Step 1: Platform Teams Set Foundation
ğŸ—ï¸ SETUP DECISION: How do we organize notification schemas?

âœ… CHOSEN: Platform-Specific Namespaces
â”œâ”€â”€ Mobile Team creates: jpmc.notifications.mobile.push
â””â”€â”€ Desktop Team creates: jpmc.notifications.desktop.rich

ğŸ’¡ WHY: Each team owns their platform expertise and user experience
Step 2: Define Platform Rules
ğŸ“‹ SCHEMA DECISION: What fields should each platform support?

âœ… MOBILE SCHEMA (mobile.push.v1):
â”œâ”€â”€ title (â‰¤25 chars) - Quick, scannable
â”œâ”€â”€ body (â‰¤20 chars) - Essential info only
â””â”€â”€ action_url - Deep link to app

âœ… DESKTOP SCHEMA (desktop.rich.v1):
â”œâ”€â”€ title (â‰¤100 chars) - Descriptive headline
â”œâ”€â”€ body (â‰¤300 chars) - Full context
â”œâ”€â”€ header, footer - Professional branding
â”œâ”€â”€ icon_url - Visual enhancement
â””â”€â”€ buttons[] - Multiple actions

ğŸ’¡ WHY: Mobile = quick alerts, Desktop = detailed information
Step 3: MyWorkspace App Integration
ğŸ”Œ INTEGRATION DECISION: How does MyWorkspace connect to the platform?

âœ… CHOSEN: Two Routes for Same App
â”œâ”€â”€ ios.jpmc.myworkspace â†’ mobile schema â†’ mobile plugin
â””â”€â”€ desktop.jpmc.myworkspace â†’ desktop schema â†’ desktop plugin

ğŸ’¡ WHY: Same business app, different technical implementations per platform
Step 4: Business Capability Mapping
ğŸ¯ CAPABILITY DECISION: How do we handle workspace bookings?

âœ… CHOSEN: Single Capability "book_a_seat"
â”œâ”€â”€ Maps to: BOTH mobile and desktop routes
â”œâ”€â”€ Business logic: Workspace booking confirmation
â””â”€â”€ Implementation: Platform-specific presentation

ğŸ’¡ WHY: One business function, multiple technical presentations
Phase 2: Runtime (Every Notification)
Step 5: Booking Event Occurs
ğŸ“± USER ACTION: John books Desk 42A through MyWorkspace mobile app

ğŸ¤” DECISION POINT: How should we notify John on his devices?

âœ… CHOSEN: Platform-Specific Payloads
â”œâ”€â”€ MyWorkspace prepares mobile-optimized content
â”œâ”€â”€ MyWorkspace prepares desktop-optimized content  
â””â”€â”€ Sends both in single API call

âŒ REJECTED ALTERNATIVES:
â”œâ”€â”€ Single payload (would need truncation/transformation)
â””â”€â”€ Auto-transformation (unpredictable results)
Step 6: Content Creation Strategy
âœï¸ CONTENT DECISION: What should each notification say?

âœ… MOBILE CONTENT (iPhone):
â”œâ”€â”€ title: "Seat Reserved"
â”œâ”€â”€ body: "Desk 42A booked" 
â””â”€â”€ action_url: "myworkspace://booking/12345"

âœ… DESKTOP CONTENT (MacBook):
â”œâ”€â”€ header: "JPMC Workspace"
â”œâ”€â”€ title: "Workspace Reservation Confirmed"
â”œâ”€â”€ body: "Your desk reservation for Desk 42A on Floor 3 has been confirmed for September 13, 2025 from 9:00 AM to 6:00 PM"
â”œâ”€â”€ footer: "Questions? Contact facilities@jpmc.com"
â”œâ”€â”€ icon_url: "https://assets.jpmc.com/icons/desk.png"
â””â”€â”€ buttons: ["View Details", "Cancel"]

ğŸ’¡ WHY: Each platform gets content optimized for its context and capabilities
Step 7: API Request Structure
json
{
  "capability": "book_a_seat",
  "recipients": [{"user_id": "john.doe@jpmc.com"}],
  "payload": [
    {
      "route": "ios.jpmc.myworkspace",
      "message": {
        "title": "Seat Reserved",
        "body": "Desk 42A booked",
        "action_url": "myworkspace://booking/12345"
      }
    },
    {
      "route": "desktop.jpmc.myworkspace", 
      "message": {
        "header": "JPMC Workspace",
        "title": "Workspace Reservation Confirmed",
        "body": "Your desk reservation for Desk 42A on Floor 3 has been confirmed for September 13, 2025 from 9:00 AM to 6:00 PM",
        "footer": "Questions? Contact facilities@jpmc.com",
        "icon_url": "https://assets.jpmc.com/icons/desk.png",
        "buttons": [{"label": "View Details", "action": "view"}]
      }
    }
  ]
}
Phase 3: Processing (System Automation)
Step 8: Platform Validation
ğŸ” VALIDATION DECISION: How do we ensure message quality?

âœ… PROCESS:
â”œâ”€â”€ Mobile payload â†’ Validate against mobile.push.v1 schema âœ…
â”œâ”€â”€ Desktop payload â†’ Validate against desktop.rich.v1 schema âœ…
â”œâ”€â”€ Check field limits, required fields, formats âœ…
â””â”€â”€ Reject if validation fails âŒ

ğŸ¤” DECISION POINT: What if validation fails?
âœ… CHOSEN: Fail fast with detailed error messages
â”œâ”€â”€ Return specific field-level errors
â”œâ”€â”€ Don't attempt auto-correction
â””â”€â”€ Let client fix and retry

ğŸ’¡ WHY: Predictable behavior, clear error handling
Step 9: Delivery Routing
ğŸš› ROUTING DECISION: How do we deliver to different platforms?

âœ… PROCESS:
â”œâ”€â”€ Mobile message â†’ mobile_plugin â†’ Firebase (FCM) â†’ John's iPhone
â”œâ”€â”€ Desktop message â†’ desktop_plugin â†’ OS API â†’ John's MacBook
â”œâ”€â”€ Each plugin specializes in its platform
â””â”€â”€ Parallel processing for speed

ğŸ’¡ WHY: Platform-specific delivery expertise and optimization
Phase 4: User Experience (Final Outcome)
Step 10: User Receives Notifications
ğŸ¤” DECISION POINT: Did we achieve optimal user experience?

Mobile Experience (iPhone):
â”Œâ”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”
â”‚ ğŸ“± MyWorkspace         â”‚  âœ… Quick recognition
â”œâ”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¤
â”‚ Seat Reserved           â”‚  âœ… Immediate understanding
â”‚ Desk 42A booked         â”‚  âœ… Essential info only
â”‚ [Tap to open app]       â”‚  âœ… Single, clear action
â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”˜

âœ… MOBILE SUCCESS CRITERIA MET:
â”œâ”€â”€ Fast to read (under 3 seconds)
â”œâ”€â”€ Clear action (tap to open)
â”œâ”€â”€ Fits mobile context (on-the-go)
