FAQs: Platform Design - Namespaces, Schemas, and Capabilities
ğŸ—ï¸ Namespace Design Questions
Q1: What is a namespace and why do we need them?
ANSWER: "Namespaces are organizational containers that group related notification functionality under clear team ownership"

NAMESPACE STRUCTURE:
â”œâ”€â”€ jpmc.notifications.mobile.push (owned by Mobile Team)
â”œâ”€â”€ jpmc.notifications.desktop.rich (owned by Desktop Team)
â”œâ”€â”€ jpmc.notifications.email.formal (owned by Email Team)
â””â”€â”€ jpmc.notifications.teams.collaborative (owned by Teams Integration Team)

WHY NEEDED:
â”œâ”€â”€ Team Ownership: Clear responsibility and expertise boundaries
â”œâ”€â”€ Governance: Different approval processes for different platforms
â”œâ”€â”€ Schema Organization: Platform-specific validation rules
â”œâ”€â”€ Support Routing: Issues go to the right team automatically
â””â”€â”€ Evolution Independence: Teams can innovate without blocking each other
Q2: How do we decide namespace boundaries?
ANSWER: "Namespaces align with platform expertise and user experience ownership"

GOOD NAMESPACE BOUNDARIES:
âœ… Platform-Based: mobile.push, desktop.rich, email.formal
   â†’ Teams have deep platform expertise
   â†’ Clear user experience ownership
   â†’ Independent technical evolution

âœ… Experience-Based: notifications.urgent, notifications.informational  
   â†’ Different user expectations and behaviors
   â†’ Different business criticality levels
   â†’ Different design and delivery requirements

âŒ BAD BOUNDARIES:
âŒ Application-Based: myworkspace.*, banking.*, hr.*
   â†’ Same platform scattered across multiple namespaces
   â†’ Inconsistent user experiences
   â†’ Duplicated platform expertise

âŒ Feature-Based: reminders.*, alerts.*, updates.*
   â†’ No clear team ownership
   â†’ Overlapping responsibilities
   â†’ Governance confusion
Q3: What happens when we need cross-namespace functionality?
ANSWER: "Capabilities bridge namespaces to provide consistent business functionality across platforms"

EXAMPLE: Workspace Booking Notification

BUSINESS NEED: Book a seat confirmation across all user devices

SOLUTION:
capability: book_a_seat
â”œâ”€â”€ Maps to: mobile namespace (quick confirmation)
â”œâ”€â”€ Maps to: desktop namespace (detailed information)
â”œâ”€â”€ Maps to: email namespace (official documentation)
â””â”€â”€ Provides: Consistent business outcome across platforms

RESULT:
â”œâ”€â”€ Same business function (booking confirmation)
â”œâ”€â”€ Platform-optimized experiences (mobile vs desktop vs email)
â”œâ”€â”€ Team ownership maintained (each team owns their namespace)
â””â”€â”€ User gets cohesive experience across all devices
ğŸ“‹ Schema Design Questions
Q4: Why do we have different schemas for mobile vs desktop?
ANSWER: "Schemas enforce platform-specific constraints and enable platform-optimized experiences"

MOBILE SCHEMA CONSTRAINTS:
â”œâ”€â”€ title: â‰¤25 characters (glanceable on small screen)
â”œâ”€â”€ body: â‰¤20 characters (quick read while multitasking)
â”œâ”€â”€ action_url: Required (single, clear next step)
â””â”€â”€ buttons: Not allowed (space constraints, touch interaction)

PURPOSE: Ensure mobile notifications are quick, scannable, actionable

DESKTOP SCHEMA CAPABILITIES:
â”œâ”€â”€ title: â‰¤100 characters (descriptive headlines)
â”œâ”€â”€ body: â‰¤300 characters (full context and details)
â”œâ”€â”€ header/footer: Professional branding and resources
â”œâ”€â”€ buttons: Multiple actions (workflow efficiency)
â””â”€â”€ icons: Visual enhancement and recognition

PURPOSE: Enable desktop notifications to be informative and workflow-integrated
Q5: What if we want to send the same content to both mobile and desktop?
ANSWER: "You can't - and that's intentional design to prevent compromised user experiences"

WHY THIS RESTRICTION EXISTS:
â”œâ”€â”€ Prevents "lowest common denominator" experiences
â”œâ”€â”€ Forces deliberate consideration of platform strengths
â”œâ”€â”€ Eliminates surprise truncations or formatting issues
â”œâ”€â”€ Ensures each platform gets optimized content

BETTER APPROACH:
Instead of: "Send same content everywhere"
Do this: "Optimize content for each platform's job"

EXAMPLE:
Business Event: John books Desk 42A

Mobile Content (awareness job):
â”œâ”€â”€ title: "Seat Reserved"
â”œâ”€â”€ body: "Desk 42A booked"

Desktop Content (planning job):  
â”œâ”€â”€ title: "Workspace Reservation Confirmed"
â”œâ”€â”€ body: "Your desk reservation for Desk 42A on Floor 3 has been confirmed for September 13, 2025"
â”œâ”€â”€ buttons: ["View Details", "Cancel", "Modify"]

RESULT: Each platform serves its user context perfectly
Q6: How do we handle schema evolution without breaking existing applications?
ANSWER: "Versioned schemas with backward compatibility and migration support"

SCHEMA VERSIONING:
â”œâ”€â”€ mobile.push.v1: Original schema (title â‰¤25, body â‰¤20)
â”œâ”€â”€ mobile.push.v2: Enhanced schema (adds priority field, emoji support)
â”œâ”€â”€ mobile.push.v3: Future schema (might add rich media support)

MIGRATION STRATEGY:
Phase 1: Deploy new schema version alongside existing
â”œâ”€â”€ Applications can choose when to upgrade
â”œâ”€â”€ Platform validates against specified version
â”œâ”€â”€ No breaking changes for existing integrations

Phase 2: Encourage adoption with new features
â”œâ”€â”€ New capabilities only available in latest schema
â”œâ”€â”€ Enhanced validation and error messages
â”œâ”€â”€ Better user experience features

Phase 3: Sunset old versions with notice
â”œâ”€â”€ 12-month deprecation notice for v1
â”œâ”€â”€ Migration support and tools provided
â”œâ”€â”€ Gradual transition, no forced breaking changes
ğŸ¯ Capability Design Questions
Q7: What's the difference between a capability and a schema?
ANSWER: "Schemas define structure rules, capabilities define business functions"

SCHEMA: "What fields and formats are allowed"
â”œâ”€â”€ Technical validation rules
â”œâ”€â”€ Field length limits  
â”œâ”€â”€ Required vs optional fields
â”œâ”€â”€ Data type constraints
â””â”€â”€ Platform-specific formatting

CAPABILITY: "What business job gets done"
â”œâ”€â”€ Business function definition
â”œâ”€â”€ Multi-platform coordination
â”œâ”€â”€ Success outcome specification  
â”œâ”€â”€ User job satisfaction
â””â”€â”€ Cross-schema consistency

EXAMPLE:
Schema: mobile.push.v1 (title â‰¤25 chars, body â‰¤20 chars, action_url required)
Capability: book_a_seat (confirms workspace reservations across all platforms)

The capability uses multiple schemas to deliver consistent business outcome
Q8: Can one capability work with multiple schemas?
ANSWER: "Yes - that's exactly how we provide consistent business functions across platforms"

CAPABILITY: learning_assignment
â”œâ”€â”€ Uses mobile.push.v1 schema â†’ Quick training awareness
â”œâ”€â”€ Uses desktop.rich.v1 schema â†’ Detailed training information  
â”œâ”€â”€ Uses email.formal.v1 schema â†’ Official assignment documentation
â””â”€â”€ Delivers consistent outcome: User successfully acknowledges training assignment

BUSINESS BENEFIT:
â”œâ”€â”€ Same business function (learning assignment)
â”œâ”€â”€ Platform-appropriate presentation (mobile vs desktop vs email)
â”œâ”€â”€ Coordinated user experience (all platforms work together)
â””â”€â”€ Unified analytics and tracking (single capability metrics)

TECHNICAL BENEFIT:
â”œâ”€â”€ Schema evolution independent per platform
â”œâ”€â”€ New platforms can be added without changing business logic
â”œâ”€â”€ Capability success measured across all platforms
â””â”€â”€ Clear separation of concerns (business vs presentation)
Q9: How do we handle capability dependencies?
ANSWER: "Design capabilities to be independent, use orchestration for complex workflows"

INDEPENDENT CAPABILITIES (Preferred):
âœ… learning_assignment: Standalone function
âœ… learning_reminder: Standalone function  
âœ… learning_completion: Standalone function

ORCHESTRATED WORKFLOWS (When needed):
Business Process: Complete learning compliance workflow
â”œâ”€â”€ Step 1: learning_assignment capability
â”œâ”€â”€ Wait: User progress monitoring
â”œâ”€â”€ Step 2: learning_reminder capability (if needed)
â”œâ”€â”€ Wait: Deadline monitoring  
â”œâ”€â”€ Step 3: learning_escalation capability (if overdue)
â”œâ”€â”€ Final: learning_completion capability (when done)

ORCHESTRATION BENEFITS:
â”œâ”€â”€ Each capability remains simple and testable
â”œâ”€â”€ Workflow can adapt based on user behavior
â”œâ”€â”€ Failed capabilities don't break entire process
â”œâ”€â”€ Easy to modify workflow without changing capabilities
â””â”€â”€ Clear success/failure points for monitoring
ğŸ”„ Integration Questions
Q10: How does an application integrate with multiple namespaces?
ANSWER: "Applications create routes into different namespaces based on their platform needs"

APPLICATION: MyWorkspace
INTEGRATION NEEDS: Send notifications to users on mobile, desktop, and email

ROUTE SETUP:
â”œâ”€â”€ ios.jpmc.myworkspace
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Namespace: jpmc.notifications.mobile.push
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Schema: mobile.push.v1  
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Plugin: mobile_plugin
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Use case: Quick booking confirmations
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ desktop.jpmc.myworkspace  
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Namespace: jpmc.notifications.desktop.rich
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Schema: desktop.rich.v1
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Plugin: desktop_plugin
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Use case: Detailed workspace information
â”‚
â””â”€â”€ email.jpmc.myworkspace
    â”œâ”€â”€ Namespace: jpmc.notifications.email.formal
    â”œâ”€â”€ Schema: email.formal.v1
    â”œâ”€â”€ Plugin: email_plugin
    â””â”€â”€ Use case: Official booking documentation

APPLICATION SENDS:
Single API call with platform-specific payloads for each route
Q11: What if we want to add a new platform (like SMS)?
ANSWER: "Create new namespace and schema, map existing capabilities, no changes to applications"

NEW PLATFORM ADDITION:
Step 1: Create SMS infrastructure
â”œâ”€â”€ Namespace: jpmc.notifications.sms.brief
â”œâ”€â”€ Schema: sms.brief.v1 (message â‰¤160 chars, phone_number required)
â”œâ”€â”€ Plugin: sms_plugin (Twilio integration)
â””â”€â”€ Team: Assign to Mobile team (similar constraints)

Step 2: Map existing capabilities  
â”œâ”€â”€ book_a_seat â†’ SMS: "Desk 42A confirmed for tomorrow"
â”œâ”€â”€ learning_assignment â†’ SMS: "Training assigned: Cybersecurity due Mar 15"
â”œâ”€â”€ meeting_reminder â†’ SMS: "Meeting in 15 mins: Room 4B"
â””â”€â”€ Each capability now supports 4 platforms

Step 3: Applications opt-in
â”œâ”€â”€ MyWorkspace can add SMS route: sms.jpmc.myworkspace
â”œâ”€â”€ Existing routes (mobile, desktop, email) unchanged
â”œâ”€â”€ Applications choose which platforms to use
â””â”€â”€ Users get notifications on preferred channels

RESULT: Platform expansion without breaking existing functionality
Q12: How do we handle errors and failures across namespaces?
ANSWER: "Isolated failure handling with graceful degradation and clear escalation paths"

FAILURE ISOLATION:
â”œâ”€â”€ Mobile namespace failure â†’ Desktop and email still work
â”œâ”€â”€ Schema validation failure â†’ Clear error to application team
â”œâ”€â”€ Plugin failure â†’ Retry logic, fallback to alternative delivery
â””â”€â”€ Capability failure â†’ Other capabilities continue working

ERROR HANDLING BY COMPONENT:

NAMESPACE ERRORS:
â”œâ”€â”€ Team ownership â†’ Route to correct support team
â”œâ”€â”€ Schema validation â†’ Detailed field-level error messages
â”œâ”€â”€ Rate limiting â†’ Graceful queuing with backpressure
â””â”€â”€ Plugin failures â†’ Automatic retry with exponential backoff

CAPABILITY ERRORS:  
â”œâ”€â”€ Partial failure â†’ Some platforms succeed, others retry
â”œâ”€â”€ Complete failure â†’ Business logic error, escalate to application team
â”œâ”€â”€ Dependency failure â†’ Clear error message with resolution steps
â””â”€â”€ Performance degradation â†’ Automatic scaling and monitoring alerts

ESCALATION PATHS:
â”œâ”€â”€ Technical issues â†’ Platform team (mobile/desktop/email)
â”œâ”€â”€ Business logic issues â†’ Application team (MyWorkspace)
â”œâ”€â”€ Infrastructure issues â†’ Platform engineering team
â””â”€â”€ User experience issues â†’ Product team with usage analytics
ğŸ“Š Governance Questions
Q13: Who approves new schemas and capabilities?
ANSWER: "Schema approval by platform teams, capability approval by platform engineering with business stakeholder sign-off"

SCHEMA APPROVAL (Platform Team Authority):
Mobile Schema Changes:
â”œâ”€â”€ Reviewer: Mobile Platform Team Lead
â”œâ”€â”€ Criteria: User experience impact, technical feasibility
â”œâ”€â”€ Timeline: 2-3 business days
â””â”€â”€ Authority: Can approve without escalation

Desktop Schema Changes:
â”œâ”€â”€ Reviewer: Desktop Platform Team Lead  
â”œâ”€â”€ Criteria: Workflow integration, information density
â”œâ”€â”€ Timeline: 2-3 business days
â””â”€â”€ Authority: Can approve without escalation

NEW CAPABILITY APPROVAL (Platform Engineering Authority):
Review Process:
â”œâ”€â”€ Business justification: Clear user need and success metrics
â”œâ”€â”€ Technical review: Architecture impact, performance considerations  
â”œâ”€â”€ Resource planning: Development effort, ongoing maintenance
â”œâ”€â”€ Stakeholder sign-off: Business owner approval
â””â”€â”€ Timeline: 1-2 weeks for complete review

ESCALATION:
â”œâ”€â”€ Cross-namespace impact â†’ Platform Architecture Review
â”œâ”€â”€ Major schema changes â†’ Platform Engineering approval
â”œâ”€â”€ High business risk â†’ Executive sponsor approval
â””â”€â”€ Compliance concerns â†’ Legal and Risk review
Q14: How do we prevent namespace and schema sprawl?
ANSWER: "Governance policies with regular reviews and consolidation opportunities"

PREVENTION POLICIES:

NAMESPACE CREATION:
â”œâ”€â”€ Must have dedicated team ownership
â”œâ”€â”€ Must serve distinct platform or user experience need
â”œâ”€â”€ Minimum 5 applications and 1000 users projected
â”œâ”€â”€ Cannot overlap with existing namespace purpose
â””â”€â”€ Annual review for utilization and value

SCHEMA CREATION:  
â”œâ”€â”€ Must have technical justification (new platform constraints)
â”œâ”€â”€ Cannot duplicate existing schema capabilities
â”œâ”€â”€ Must have migration path from existing schemas
â”œâ”€â”€ Backward compatibility requirements
â””â”€â”€ Sunset plan for deprecated versions

CAPABILITY CREATION:
â”œâ”€â”€ Must solve underserved user need with >1000 users
â”œâ”€â”€ Cannot duplicate existing capability function
â”œâ”€â”€ Must provide measurable business value
â”œâ”€â”€ Cross-platform consistency requirements
â””â”€â”€ Success metrics defined upfront

REGULAR REVIEW PROCESS:
â”œâ”€â”€ Quarterly namespace utilization review
â”œâ”€â”€ Annual schema consolidation opportunities  
â”œâ”€â”€ Biannual capability effectiveness assessment
â””â”€â”€ Continuous monitoring for redundancy and overlap
ğŸš€ Summary: Design Benefits
Namespaces Provide:
âœ… Clear team ownership and expertise
âœ… Independent evolution and innovation
âœ… Appropriate governance for different platforms
âœ… Isolated failure handling and support
Schemas Provide:
âœ… Platform-optimized user experiences
âœ… Validation and quality assurance
âœ… Versioned evolution without breaking changes
âœ… Technical constraints that drive better design
Capabilities Provide:
âœ… Consistent business functions across platforms
âœ… User-centric organization of functionality
âœ… Unified analytics and success measurement
âœ… Clear integration points for applications
Result: A notification platform that scales with organizational needs while delivering excellent user experiences through deliberate design constraints and clear ownership boundaries.

