### **Q10: What happens if the system goes down?**

**ANSWER:** "We have backups and fallbacks, like having multiple routes to get to work"
REDUNDANCY LAYERS:

PRIMARY SYSTEM (Normal Operation):
â”œâ”€â”€ Main notification servers running
â”œâ”€â”€ All platforms working normally
â”œâ”€â”€ Messages delivered within seconds
â””â”€â”€ Full functionality available

BACKUP SYSTEM (If Primary Fails):
â”œâ”€â”€ Automatic switch to backup servers â”œâ”€â”€ Queue messages until primary recovered â”œâ”€â”€ Deliver backlogged messages when system restored â””â”€â”€ Users might see slight delays but don't lose messages

FALLBACK SYSTEM (If Both Primary and Backup Fail):
â”œâ”€â”€ Critical notifications can fall back to email
â”œâ”€â”€ Emergency contact system for urgent alerts
â”œâ”€â”€ Manual notification processes for compliance-critical items
â””â”€â”€ Business continuity maintained for essential functions

REAL-WORLD ANALOGY:

GETTING TO WORK:
â”œâ”€â”€ Primary route: Highway (fastest, normal choice)
â”œâ”€â”€ Backup route: Main streets (slower but reliable)
â”œâ”€â”€ Fallback route: Back roads (slow but always works)
â””â”€â”€ Emergency option: Work from home

NOTIFICATION DELIVERY: â”œâ”€â”€ Primary: Real-time platform delivery â”œâ”€â”€ Backup: Queued delivery when system restored
â”œâ”€â”€ Fallback: Email delivery for critical messages â””â”€â”€ Emergency: Manual phone calls for urgent items

WHAT USERS EXPERIENCE:
â”œâ”€â”€ Normal times: Instant, optimized notifications
â”œâ”€â”€ Minor issues: Slightly delayed but complete delivery
â”œâ”€â”€ Major issues: Fall back to email with explanation
â”œâ”€â”€ Critical situations: Personal contact for urgent matters
â””â”€â”€ Always informed about system status and expected resolution


