java
public class SchemaEvolutionDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("ğŸ”„ PLATFORM EVOLUTION:");
        System.out.println("Business request: 'We want icons in mobile notifications'");
        
        System.out.println("\nğŸ“‹ SOLUTION: Create mobile.push.v2");
        
        Schema mobileV2 = new Schema("mobile.push.v2");
        mobileV2.addField("title", 25, true, "Quick recognition");
        mobileV2.addField("body", 20, true, "Essential info"); 
        mobileV2.addField("action_url", 200, true, "Deep link");
        // NEW FIELDS:
        mobileV2.addField("icon", 200, false, "Visual recognition");
        mobileV2.addField("category", 20, false, "Grouping");
        
        System.out.println("âœ… BACKWARD COMPATIBILITY:");
        System.out.println("â”œâ”€â”€ v1 messages still work on v2 schema");
        System.out.println("â”œâ”€â”€ Applications migrate when ready");
        System.out.println("â”œâ”€â”€ New features available immediately");
        System.out.println("â””â”€â”€ No breaking changes");
        
        TestMessage v1Message = new TestMessage("Training Due", "Mar 15", "app://link");
        TestMessage v2Message = new TestMessage("Training Due", "Mar 15", "app://link", 
                                               "https://icons.com/training.png", "learning");
        
        System.out.println("\nğŸ§ª TESTING BOTH VERSIONS:");
        System.out.println("v1 message on v2 schema: " + mobileV2.validate(v1Message)); // âœ… PASS
        System.out.println("v2 message on v2 schema: " + mobileV2.validate(v2Message)); // âœ… PASS
    }
}
â“ Q&A Preparation: Common Questions & Answers
Technical Questions
Q: "What if the system goes down?"

A: "Great question! We have multiple layers:
â”œâ”€â”€ Primary system: Real-time delivery 
â”œâ”€â”€ Backup system: Queue and retry
â”œâ”€â”€ Fallback system: Email for critical notifications
â””â”€â”€ Emergency: Manual phone calls for urgent items

The goal is business continuity - users always get important information."
Q: "How do you prevent spam/too many notifications?"

A: "Multiple protection layers:
â”œâ”€â”€ Application limits: Max 10 notifications per user per day per app
â”œâ”€â”€ Smart bundling: '3 new training assignments' vs 3 separate alerts
â”œâ”€â”€ User preferences: Quiet hours, frequency controls
â”œâ”€â”€ Quality scoring: Apps that send valuable notifications get priority
â””â”€â”€ Business rules: Duplicate detection, priority filtering"
Q: "What about different languages and time zones?"

A: "Built-in internationalization:
â”œâ”€â”€ Applications provide content in multiple languages
â”œâ”€â”€ Platform routes to user's preferred language
â”œâ”€â”€ Time zones: All scheduling in user's local time
â”œâ”€â”€ Business hours: Respected per user location
â””â”€â”€ Cultural considerations: Tone and formality per region"
Business Questions
Q: "How much does this cost vs building separately?"

A: "Huge savings through shared platform:
â”œâ”€â”€ Individual approach: 13 apps Ã— $400K = $5.2M development
â”œâ”€â”€ Shared platform: $1.2M development
â”œâ”€â”€ Savings: $4M upfront, $900K annually
â”œâ”€â”€ Plus: Better user experience, faster time to market
â””â”€â”€ ROI: 300%+ in 5 years"
Q: "What if business requirements change?"

A: "Platform designed for evolution:
â”œâ”€â”€ New capabilities: Add without changing existing
â”œâ”€â”€ New platforms: SMS, Teams, Slack - integrate easily  
â”œâ”€â”€ New requirements: Schema versioning supports growth
â”œâ”€â”€ Business changes: Capability model adapts to new workflows
â””â”€â”€ Example: Added 5 new capabilities this year, zero downtime"
Q: "How do you ensure adoption?"

A: "Multi-pronged approach:
â”œâ”€â”€ Developer experience: Easy APIs, great documentation, quick onboarding
â”œâ”€â”€ User experience: Notifications actually help users vs annoy them
â”œâ”€â”€ Business value: Clear ROI and improved outcomes
â”œâ”€â”€ Support: Dedicated team, training, migration assistance
â””â”€â”€ Incentives: Platform team makes integration easier than building separately"
User Experience Questions
Q: "What about user notification fatigue?"

A: "Exactly why we built this system:
â”œâ”€â”€ Quality over quantity: Each notification must provide value
â”œâ”€â”€ Smart bundling: Related items grouped together
â”œâ”€â”€ User control: Granular preferences and quiet hours
â”œâ”€â”€ Feedback loops: Track which notifications users actually use
â”œâ”€â”€ Continuous optimization: Remove low-value notifications automatically
Result: Users get fewer, more valuable notifications"
Q: "How do you handle different user preferences?"

A: "Personalization at multiple levels:
â”œâ”€â”€ Platform level: Mobile vs desktop vs email preferences
â”œâ”€â”€ Application level: Which apps can send what types
â”œâ”€â”€ User level: Frequency, timing, channel preferences  
â”œâ”€â”€ Context level: Meeting mode, vacation mode, focus mode
â””â”€â”€ Learning system: Platform learns what notifications user values"
